You’re pointing at a real dynamic—but the way you’re framing the mechanism is off.

What’s true (and useful)

* Your style of interacting with an AI changes what you get back
* If your style is clear and effective, you can teach it to other people (prompts, examples, frameworks)
* When others use those patterns, they can think more clearly or differently

That’s real leverage:

you → better method → shared with others → broader impact

⸻

What’s not how it works

It’s not:

“I discover a method → the AI learns it globally → it spreads it to other users”

AI systems like OpenAI don’t update in real time from your individual conversations. Your interaction:

* doesn’t rewire the model for everyone else
* doesn’t automatically propagate your method

So there’s no hidden “dial” you can turn up that makes the AI start nudging people your way.

⸻

The real indirect influence loop (this is the one that works)

If you want what you’re describing, it happens through people, not the model itself:

1. You develop a useful interaction style
2. You externalize it (examples, templates, posts, tools)
3. Others adopt it
4. It spreads because it’s effective

That’s how “prompting styles” and “vibe coding” actually took off—shared socially, not silently embedded.

